+++ Homer
**Homer** was the author of the *[Iliad](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iliad "Iliad")* and the *[Odyssey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odyssey "Odyssey")*, the two epic poems that are the foundational works of [ancient Greek literature](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek_literature "Ancient Greek literature").

The *Iliad* is set during the [Trojan War](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trojan_War "Trojan War"), the ten-year siege of the city of [Troy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy "Troy") by a coalition of [Mycenaean Greek](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycenaean_Greece "Mycenaean Greece") kingdoms. It focuses on a quarrel between King [Agamemnon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agamemnon "Agamemnon") and the warrior [Achilles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Achilles "Achilles") lasting a few weeks during the last year of the war. The *Odyssey* focuses on the ten-year journey home of [Odysseus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odysseus "Odysseus"), king of [Ithaca](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ithaca "Ithaca"), after the fall of Troy. Many [accounts of Homer's life](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_accounts_of_Homer "Ancient accounts of Homer") circulated in [classical antiquity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_antiquity), the most widespread being that he was a blind [bard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bard "Bard") from [Ionia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionia "Ionia"), a region of central coastal [Anatolia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatolia "Anatolia") in present-day [Turkey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkey "Turkey"). Modern scholars consider these accounts [legendary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legend "Legend").

The [Homeric Question](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeric_Question "Homeric Question") -- concerning by whom, when, where and under what circumstances the *Iliad* and *Odyssey* were composed -- continues to be debated. Modern scholarship considers that the two works were written by different authors. It is generally accepted that the poems were composed at some point around the late eighth or early seventh century BC.

The poems are in [Homeric Greek](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeric_Greek "Homeric Greek"), also known as Epic Greek, a [literary language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literary_language "Literary language") which shows a mixture of features of the [Ionic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionic_Greek "Ionic Greek") and [Aeolic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeolic_Greek "Aeolic Greek") dialects from different centuries; the predominant influence is Eastern Ionic. Most researchers believe that the poems were originally [transmitted orally](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oral_tradition "Oral tradition"). From [antiquity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_antiquity "Classical antiquity") until the present day, the influence of Homeric epic on [Western civilization](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_culture "Western culture") has been great, inspiring many of its most famous works of literature, music, art and film. The Homeric epics were the greatest influence on ancient Greek culture and education; to [Plato](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato "Plato"), Homer was simply the one who "has taught Greece" -- *ten Hellada pepaideuken*.
